<hl>
<seg id=1> Bangkok To Resume Elevated Railway Project </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AGENCE FRANCE PRESSE WIRE Bangkok) The Thai Ministry of Transport and Communication announced yesterday that it will demand that Hong Kong listed company Hopewell Group, contractor for Bangkok's elevated railway and roadworks system, pay a penalty in the amount of 6.8 billion U.S. dollars (about 11 billion Singapore dollars) for not completing its contract on time. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Pradit Phataraprasit, deputy minister of transport and communications, said that the Ministry of Transport and Communications and Thai National Railways had the right to demand 6.8 billion U.S. dollars in compensation from Hopewell Group for losses due to delays in the project. Thailand says that Hopewell is has completed only 12 percent of the project over the last eight years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Since the economic crisis in Thailand, Hopewell Group, due to financial disputes exacerbated by the devaluation of the Thai baht and land requisition disputes, has had numerous unsuccessful negotiations with relevant Thai authorities. The Thai government halted its contract with Hopewell in January of this year. </seg>
<seg id=5> Hopewell has demanded 100 billion Thai baht (about 4.2 billion Singapore dollars) from the Thai government to compensate for funds invested and the completed portion of the project over the last eight years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The Thai government said yesterday that it plans to resume the 3.2 billion U.S. dollar project, but is considering scaling down its size. </seg>
<seg id=7> It will not invite Hopewell to join in the project. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Phataraprasit said that the German government and the German Development Bank (KFW) are interested in reviving the huge project, and have decided to provide 100 million Thai baht in funds for a feasibility study of Bangkok's elevated train and roadway system project. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Siemens AG of Germany is currently working with a local company in Thailand on a different 23 kilometer-long electric train project. </seg>
</p>
